# The square of opposition

For two thousand years, students learned the logic of *all*, *no*, and
*some* from one diagram. The corners are the four categorical forms; the
edges say how they conflict or cooperate — and here, every edge is checked
by the engine rather than taken on trust.

square men mortal

# Where Aristotle and modern logic part ways

The diagonals — the contradictories — hold outright: *All men are mortal*
and *Some men are not mortal* always disagree. But every other edge quietly
assumes that at least one man exists. Aristotle granted that for free;
modern logic does not, and the amber edges show exactly what his assumption
was buying.

The same divide decides four famous syllogisms. Darapti was valid for every
medieval logician — and modern logic refutes it with an empty class:

All unicorns are horses. All unicorns are magical. Therefore, some magical are horses.

The countermodel is the whole story: a world with no unicorns at all makes
both premises true — vacuously — and the conclusion false. Grant Aristotle
his non-empty classes, and Darapti is restored.
